  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970\n- Requires financial institutions to assist U.S. government agencies in detecting and preventing money laundering\n- Mandates reporting of certain transactions\n\n2. The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Made money laundering a federal crime\n- Established criminal penalties for money laundering activities\n\n3. Title III of the USA PATRIOT Act\n- Expanded anti-money laundering regulations\n- Enhanced requirements for financial institutions to implement anti-money laundering programs\n\n4. The Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n- Updated and modernized previous anti-money laundering laws\n- Expanded reporting requirements and increased penalties\n\nAt the federal level, money laundering is primarily prosecuted under 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956 and \u00a7 1957, which define specific money laundering offenses and establish criminal penalties.\n\nThese statutes collectively provide a comprehensive legal framework for preventing, detecting, and prosecuting money laundering activities in the United States.\n\nState governments may also have additional money laundering statutes that complement federal laws.",
